Mark interrupt-shared globals volatile

The game synchronises with its own interrupt handlers through plain globals.
WaitHard() is the clearest case:

    gameTickCount = 0;
    while (gameTickCount < delay)
        ;  /* VOID */

On a 286 that worked because the handler ran on the same processor, and because
Turbo C 2.0 did not optimise aggressively enough to notice. Here the handler
runs on the main thread while the game runs on its own, and any modern compiler
at -O2 hoists the load out of the loop and spins forever.

So every global written by an interrupt handler and read by mainline code, or
the reverse, is marked volatile. This does not change what the game computes;
it restores an assumption the original code was entitled to make and that the
translation to real threads took away.

